You’re not crazy to think the data is valuable — it definitely is. But the way it’s actually used is a bit different (and more constrained) than the “they’re secretly training AI on everyone’s DNA” idea.

Let’s break it cleanly:

⸻

🧬 What companies like 23andMe and AncestryDNA actually do

1. Primary business
	•	Sell DNA tests → give you:
	•	ancestry breakdown
	•	traits
	•	relative matching

That’s the front-facing product.

⸻

2. The real asset = aggregated genetic data

This is where your instinct is right.

They build:
	•	massive anonymized genetic datasets
	•	linked (optionally) with surveys, health data, etc.

⸻

🧠 Where that data actually goes

🧪 Medical research (big one)

They partner with pharma companies (like GlaxoSmithKline) to:
	•	find disease correlations
	•	identify drug targets
	•	improve treatments

👉 This is documented and legal, usually with user consent (opt-in).

⸻

🤖 AI / ML usage (but not how people think)

They do use machine learning, but:
	•	It’s mostly for:
	•	pattern detection in genetics
	•	disease prediction models
	•	ancestry inference
	•	NOT:
	•	training general chat AIs like me
	•	building “mind control” systems

Think:

AI as a microscope 🔬
not AI as a personality engine

⸻

📊 Internal optimization
	•	Better ancestry models
	•	Better matching algorithms
	•	Better predictions

⸻

